<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900730-0080</DOCNO><DOCID>900730-0080.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Thorn EMI PLC:   Results Seen Weak for Half   But Strong for Fiscal Year</HL><DATE>07/30/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   U.THN</CO><LP>   Thorn EMI PLC of Britain, a music, home-appliance rentaland lighting concern, is being hurt by soft domestic consumerdemand and stiff competition in some product areas world-wideand expects weak first-half earnings, Colin Southgate,chairman and chief executive officer, said.   But Mr. Southgate told shareholders at the annual meetingthat Thorn should show improved earnings for fiscal 1991. Forthe year ended March 31, Thorn had pretax profit of #318million ($576.9 million), up 9.8% from a year earlier.</LP><TEXT>   Thorn has been selling interests that it considers to beoutside its mainstream businesses. Thorn recently said it isholding talks to sell its Holophane S.A. pressed glasssubsidiary and in May said it was negotiating the sale of itslighting unit to GTE Corp., Stamford, Conn.   Both of Thorn's two main businesses, recorded music andappliance rentals, &quot;are performing well on a world-wide basisand in line with plan,&quot; Mr. Southgate said.</TEXT></DOC>